{
  "title": "Formen, Kreise, Diagramme",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f2fd760ab0a7760a",
      "text": "The graphic arsenal of sociology, which for a long time consisted mainly of cross tables and distribution diagrams, was expanded by systems theory, at the latest with [[Dirk Baecker]]'s \"Form and Forms of Communication\" (2005), with those striking \"form\" representations with their nested hooks and lines leading around the corners, through which many systems theory texts stand out from their sociological surroundings in a typical way in terms of design."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "90df7232668b9269",
      "text": "While interest is usually and obviously focused on explaining or understanding what is shown in these graphic figures, whose form can be traced back to the mathematical notation developed by George Spencer-Brown in the 1960s (Spencer-Brown 1979), the theoretical status of these formal graphics is rarely discussed: Are they \"formalisms\" (Baecker 2005, 60) of a mathematical calculation of the pragmatic redundancies of human communication (Baecker 2014, following Watzlawick et al. 2017), are they \"equations\" (Karafillidis 2015, 39), \"symbols\" (Simon 2018, 25)?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4f05c688e9aab752",
      "text": "This article proposes that systems theory should understand its handling of these graphs of forms as diagrammatic practice in the context of the distinction between symbolization/formalization (Carnap 1968). In other words, these form-figures should not be understood as formalisms, i.e. as perspectives on an as yet unwritten formal calculus of the social, but – contrary to the self-description of this practice (Baecker 2005, 11 f.) – as symbolizing diagrams."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f9965b4b5adf9cb2",
      "text": "The article explores the impression that the use of form figures may be more loosely tied to mathematics than is generally assumed or claimed and argues that this use should not be interpreted as \"applications\" of the formal calculus of the Laws of Form, but rather as \"analogies\" that have been put into operation. In addition to the heuristic value of such figure designs, further advantages of such \"operative imagery\" (Krämer 2009) are elaborated: It offers the possibility to abandon some theoretical trajectories of a spatial metaphoric, as, according to the thesis, becomes operationally effective in the common interpretation of the concept of the \"two-sided form\"."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c4578c2a5b18c4af",
      "text": "In this sense, this essay is a contribution to theory design in the strictest sense of the word."
    },
