    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "46025c1461637478",
      "text": "**Abstract** What is the role of the „form” figures familiar from many systems theory texts? This paper observes (bypassing conventional theoretical self-descriptions of the role of „forms”) the actual use of these “forms” in their various modes of notation. In this perspective, the use of the “forms” is not an application of a calculus of the social. The forms do not function as logical expressions. Rather, the thesis is that these figures can be interpreted as diagrams that serve as objects of comparison for systems theory, like Wittgenstein’s “language games” in the philosophy of language. In this sense, the article makes the proposal to understand diagrammatic handling as a fruitful heuristic practice, as a (system-theoretical) form of design thinking.\n\n    In fact, when one starts from the beginning,\n\n    there is nothing to learn.\n\n    There is everything to unlearn,\n\n    but nothing to learn.\n\n    George Spencer-Brown\n"
    }
