      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "f2fd760ab0a7760a",
        "text": "The graphic arsenal of sociology, which for a long time consisted mainly of cross tables and distribution diagrams, was expanded by systems theory, at the latest with Dirk Baecker's \"Form and Forms of Communication\" (2005), with those striking \"form\" representations[1] with their nested hooks and lines leading around the corners, through which many systems theory texts stand out from their sociological surroundings in a typical way in terms of design. While interest is usually and obviously focused on explaining or understanding what is shown in these graphic figures, whose form can be traced back to the mathematical notation developed by George Spencer-Brown in the 1960s (Spencer-Brown 1979), the theoretical status of these formal graphics is rarely discussed: Are they \"formalisms\" (Baecker 2005, 60) of a mathematical calculation of the pragmatic redundancies of human communication (Baecker 2014, following Watzlawick et al. 2017), are they \"equations\" (Karafillidis 2015, 39), \"symbols\" (Simon 2018, 25)?"
      },
      "date": 1701771479384
